Rate the chapter's metaphor and imagery variety on a scale of 1–10.

This dimension measures whether the prose draws from multiple imagery registers or relies on a single dominant family. A chapter where every comparison is a gambling metaphor ("the odds," "the house," "roll the die," "the deck," "a bad bet") scores low even if each individual metaphor is well-crafted. A chapter that moves between sensory registers — gambling, bodily, architectural, natural, mechanical, textile — scores high.

IMPORTANT: This is about variety of figurative language, not quantity. A chapter with 3 vivid metaphors from 3 different registers scores higher than a chapter with 12 metaphors all from the same register.

